Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament has today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the doors to the incarceration of the minister, but the parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes at second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison by the alleged signing of an agreement with Russia that is detrimental to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet final, and the Court of Appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there were doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code with which the former Prime Minister was convicted was supported by 147 Members in the vote.
For its adoption, 226 votes were called for.
