How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recreation and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists were therefore on holiday to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime turned to the west and the journeys of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at that time, but one should put on the queue with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "known well-known" in the agency.
Still wasn't all earned.
The so-called "change promise" that was the condition for travel to the West was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without exchange guarantee, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The large majority of the Czechs spent their vacations in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs would buy. This custom still persists.
The way of travel of the Czechs has suffered a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was no longer for us to spend vacations in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It turns out in a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that to the currently favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia since then.
In the early 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European States, causing a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovakians, for a long time, did not see the trips to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least one moment.
For example, in Paris, the Czech groups slept in the parks in campaign shops, as our incomes then did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was taking with you food (contained, embittered, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy freely Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it also average wages, which in around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in the demand for travel, agencies started regularly from 1997 to prepare travel using charter flights, which made it incredible to lower the prices of travel compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90s last century, the Czechs had already traveled without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutional tourism took place in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have made distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States eliminated visas for Czech tourists, thereby becoming among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head on travel abroad, including the expenses on the residence site.
