The walls have eyes: How the researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the extreme right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another type of anti-immigration point of view.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having committed a murder in Norway in July, who left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: he had spent most of his time in front of his computer, talking to some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - you just have to go on Facebook.
"We realize that it was not so difficult to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British DEMOS study centre.
Facebook's personal information alliance is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific precision - the way vendors have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then they were directed to ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
On arrival through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study over 10,000 followers of 14 extreme right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a completely new way to do an investigation," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online right-wing supporters tend to be young, men and angry with immigration.
However, in a kind of turn, "those who combine their online activity with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind the computer screen".
The work of DEMOS is just an example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in "I like", messages on walls and state updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "supernova of data" is generating an increase in research, pushing the number of academic works with the name of the site in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you could not approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you tried to investigate people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You should go through the party, and they would never allow you access," says Bartlett.
"Facebook eliminates all that--you're going to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and his colleagues found that university students who talked about their Facebook drunken practices had a significantly greater risk of drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential advisors, could control the site and intervene to help a student who publishs too many state updates with their drunks.
"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Health, Behavior and Development of the Child at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, Washington Post said.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk that would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "pinching" to its own population to get data.
The Site Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in mid-2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (principally using information that can be accessed - digital freedom defenders long ago that they argue that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice to be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that an investigator might be examining their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study that took place with students' public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was just between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even off-line, there is no guarantee that a subject of research is being completely honest.
