MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Directs Social Security an investigation to discover the gender of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called 'Genetic Protocol on Obesity of Children and Adolescents', which will enable you to count on markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the 21st Century National Medical Centre, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by experts and graduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Research Centre and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Political Institute (IPN).
The investigation calls for the participation of the population whether or not they are legally resident, to visit the participating sports units of IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the sports unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Mexico Pontient) and that since 8 October, the activity has been carried out in the sports unit Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of meeting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independent Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (south of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research was to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify in children and young Mexicans risk factors to prevent the emergence of degenerative chronic diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day, he stated that the goal was to gather three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 with the consent and supervision of their parents for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and heredofamily history of diseases, with the aim of avoiding risk factors that cause suffering such as diabetes or renal failure.
It detailed that the Saturdays apply to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure taking, glucose determination, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify genes associated with child obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals over the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity in children and 47 per cent in girls; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed', the IMSS expert pointed out.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers was that the country ' s population differed from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 per cent of American Indian heritage, 30 per cent European and five per cent African, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in fat form.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, allowing them to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearms, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic changes and even prediabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it in writing to the parents, to whom each of the measurements and changes in the life-style that must be made to prevent diseases are explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic suffering: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remains most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the increased consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tumbles, bread, pizza, burger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM Asphalt would avoid bashes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM Chemicals College, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent to the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand baths each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, UNAM's Chemical Faculty (FQ) researcher, who ensured that if the construction and maintenance process of an asphaltic floor is appropriate, the baths could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
In his conference A technological opinion of the baches, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, indicated that the laboratory at its post develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Mr Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and thus the formation of bakes.
He explained that asphalt, the most heavy part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, one of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrades its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrades has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes fractured, added.
The above means that in the streets asphalt resistance is not uniform, but is being changed during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineer warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, consisting of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, composed of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compact.
Each of the stones that constitute the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
When the vehicles pass and effort is generated, they allow the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt would spread even better, the chemical engineer thought.
On the asphaltic folder, it abounded, placed a last layer called a rolling folder, which is made of fine stone material, that is, a sand that also baths in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the vehicle beams, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
As part of the floor that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling stock also requires the proper thickness and the material that is made must be taken care of.
