The world-wide chip card hall begins on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an increase of 11% in global card sales with microprocessors (bank cards, SIM card phones, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to Eurosmart Cabinet calculations.
The most powerful segment is that of uncontacted technology, which allows you to subscribe to common transport or purchases simply by approaching the card to a reader.
This year will sell around the world 460 million cards with no contact chip, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share should continue to increase in 2012 (an estimated 580 million units) and represent about 10% of the world market for chip cards (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long been relegated to the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the non-contact payment sector.
About 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 visa cards are being used without contact.
But the big surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million Pass MasterCards this year without contact.
In order to make the top move, however, banks need to make it available to their customers.
"There are two large French establishments that have been committed to systematically spreading in the future, among their customers, bank cards equipped with the system without contact," Gérard Nebouy, Director General of Visa Europe France, announced.
Banks try to pay by mobile phone
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
There are currently few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology that are essential to the transaction.
"They're laughing."
"But you should finally experience a real growth next year."
"We predict that between 80 million and 120 million units will be sold in 2012 worldwide," explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The Agricultural Credit Bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and collaborators will be matched with a fund that allows payment without contact.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the General Society has also said yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact through their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, which has been suspected for a long time, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs Abdelkader Messahel even stated that Argel "has the certainty already".
"The way both organizations operate and the reports of intelligence services demonstrate that they are cooperating," he explained, without providing any further details.
Paris seems to have reached a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the passageways.
Rapted at a restaurant in Niamey by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the following day along with several of his kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the wake of the intervention, French and Nigerian researchers discovered a number of telephone chips belonging to terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates a number of partners based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers especially captured the interest of the researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, with Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly expect to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect has enjoyed financial and intellectual support from outside and that it is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" have been increasingly evident in the evolution and speech of Boko Haram or its operating modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex cameras or explosive devices and the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting from Washington, has since been pressuring Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
In fact, the Nigerian authorities have spent time considering the group as a community of illuminators of little interest.
A Quick Success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in the case, "Western education is a sin"), it encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is experiencing rapid success.
It is politicized and demands strict respect for the Sharia, while its militants are launched against the evil central government.
The latter are primarily aimed at churches, bars and administrations.
In 2009, the Boko Haram militants were particularly active and the attacks on the police stations multiplied.
Abuya's reaction was, as usual, generalized.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Joseph, arrested in life, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its waters from the north.
The past Christmas claims an attack that causes 80 deaths in Jos and then another one in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular the police-protected headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first such attack.
In August, the United Nations local headquarters became its first international goal.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would cover from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, concerns all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somalis of Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppe warned him against Boko Haram and said he was ready to "share all the information".
