The North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which communicates directly Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with a great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on Baltic shores, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, in the opening of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
In symbolic terms, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the valve wheel that controls the entry of Russian gas into the network of Western Europe.
With this new pipeline, it will each year reach 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas additional to Western Europe through a first 1224 km radius that communicates the St Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, the possibility of building a third tube by the same route is already discussed.
For Gazprom, the finalization of this huge work presents areas of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow direct supply of gas to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between the Europeans of the east and the west.
In just five years, Russia has known how to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," said François Fillon during the gas pipeline opening, demonstrating to what extent the large gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles in the faces of the Gazprom directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline also implies a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It is located at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, with caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It also required extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but the project managers gave up the project because the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be established permanently in the sea in front of its shores.
"If you have it, we'll stop the gas step in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that an escape will occur, since they have planned joints that, according to forecasts, they will have a flight every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device operating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a pure, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three complete days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, provide accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any type of repair.
The flow of gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and at the output of 100 bars.
Five companies have united their forces to be able to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which holds 51% of the stakes.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each), joined her.
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to that company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, all gas transport capacities.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually being transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be €7.400 million for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are certain that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom assumes the risk of spending alone.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas to arrive before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
Total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Made half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine book is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged over time.
However, Moleskine books with the current aspect were born... in 1997.
The Italian company modo modo, based in Milan, at that time decided to launch a book of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then company consultant, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The book is inspired by an old production technique, the soft skin skin (top skin), which refers to a baby cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of book was highly appreciated by writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the vanguardist artists until the twentieth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode.
And he succeeded.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years has remained far away, in which only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open spirit and cult.
The small Italian company, which had 12 workers at its beginnings, now has about 100 and since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its bookshelves, from Fnac to the small shops in the city center, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and need to write, despite the growth of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with Moleskine's development: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists present their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard tapes, based on the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, cylinders, computer funds... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of Persons with Disabilities begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Discouragement?
"No," said Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress achieved 15 years ago is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice the rate but three times the average.
"However, there's still a lot to do."
It should be noted that the disabled continue to face numerous obstacles to accessing employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished the bachelor's degree and only 10,000 of the 2.3 million students in higher education are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for disabled people, compared to 38 per cent of the average.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the labour world and that "consist of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; people's minds are advancing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur Association for the City indicated that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 employees are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set out in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"Now we have reached around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The evidence: the number of establishment "subjected to this contribution" as well as the amounts disbursed has decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, particularly among the major groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of the companies with between 20 and 49 workers have employees with disabilities in their template, compared with 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
